		// Handle different message types

			// First entry - main user request
			entry.RequestSummary = "Task Request: " + msg.Text
			entry.AskSay = `"say": "text"`
			entry.Text = msg.Text
			entry.ClineAction = "Task Description"

		} else if msg.Type == "say" && msg.Say == "user_feedback" && msg.Text != "" {

			entry.ClineAction = "User Feedback"
			entry.ToolUsed = "N/A"
			apiCosts = append(apiCosts, entry)
			requestCounter++
		} else if msg.Type == "say" && msg.Say == "api_req_started" && msg.Text != "" {
			// API request entries
			var apiData APIRequestData
			if err := json.Unmarshal([]byte(msg.Text), &apiData); err == nil {
				totalCost += apiData.Cost
				entry.RequestSummary = "API Request: " + apiData.Request[:min(50, len(apiData.Request))] + "..."
				entry.AskSay = `"say": "api_req_started"`
				entry.Text = msg.Text
				entry.RequestCost = apiData.Cost
				entry.TotalCost = totalCost
				entry.ContextTokensUsed = apiData.TokensIn + apiData.TokensOut
				entry.ClineAction = "API request started"
				entry.ToolUsed = "API Request"
				entry.Phase = "Completion"
				entry.SearchTermInTranscript = "api_request"
				entry.CostNotes = "ACTUAL cost from Cline interface"
				apiCosts = append(apiCosts, entry)
				requestCounter++
			}
		} else if msg.Type == "ask" && msg.Text != "" {

			entry.RequestSummary = ""

			entry.Phase = "Exploration"
			entry.SearchTermInTranscript = "ask"
			apiCosts = append(apiCosts, entry)
			requestCounter++

	}

#!/bin/bash

# Auto Cost Update Script for Cline Tasks
# Automatically extracts real API costs from Cline's ui_messages.json files
# and updates the cost CSV without user intervention

set -e

# Configuration
CLINE_TASKS_DIR="/Users/emma/Library/Application Support/Code/User/globalStorage/saoudrizwan.claude-dev/tasks"

# Find the most recent task directory first
LATEST_TASK=$(ls -1 "$CLINE_TASKS_DIR" | sort -n | tail -1)

# Convert task ID (Unix timestamp in milliseconds) to readable date
TASK_TIMESTAMP_MS=$LATEST_TASK
TASK_TIMESTAMP_S=$((TASK_TIMESTAMP_MS / 1000))
DATETIME=$(date -r $TASK_TIMESTAMP_S +"%Y-%m-%d_%H-%M-%S")

CSV_FILE="logs/task_${LATEST_TASK}_${DATETIME}_costs.csv"
LATEST_CSV="logs/request_costs.csv"
BACKUP_CSV="logs/request_costs_backup.csv"

# Colors for output
RED='\033[0;31m'
GREEN='\033[0;32m'
YELLOW='\033[1;33m'
NC='\033[0m' # No Color

echo -e "${GREEN}üîç Auto Cost Tracker - Extracting real API costs...${NC}"

# Create logs directory if it doesn't exist
mkdir -p logs

# Backup existing CSV
if [ -f "$CSV_FILE" ]; then
    cp "$CSV_FILE" "$BACKUP_CSV"
    echo -e "${YELLOW}üìã Backed up existing CSV to $BACKUP_CSV${NC}"
fi

# Find the most recent task directory
LATEST_TASK=$(ls -1 "$CLINE_TASKS_DIR" | sort -n | tail -1)
LATEST_TASK_PATH="$CLINE_TASKS_DIR/$LATEST_TASK"

if [ ! -d "$LATEST_TASK_PATH" ]; then
    echo -e "${RED}‚ùå No task directory found at $LATEST_TASK_PATH${NC}"
    exit 1
fi

echo -e "${GREEN}üìÅ Processing latest task: $LATEST_TASK${NC}"

# Check if ui_messages.json exists
UI_MESSAGES_FILE="$LATEST_TASK_PATH/ui_messages.json"
if [ ! -f "$UI_MESSAGES_FILE" ]; then
    echo -e "${RED}‚ùå ui_messages.json not found in $LATEST_TASK_PATH${NC}"
    exit 1
fi

# Compile and run Go cost parser
echo -e "${YELLOW}üîß Compiling Go cost parser...${NC}"
cd tools/cost-parser
go build -o ../../cost_parser main.go
cd ../..

if [ ! -f "./cost_parser" ]; then
    echo -e "${RED}‚ùå Failed to compile Go cost parser${NC}"
    exit 1
fi

# Extract costs using Go program
echo -e "${YELLOW}üìä Extracting costs from ui_messages.json...${NC}"
./cost_parser "$UI_MESSAGES_FILE" "$CSV_FILE"

# Clean up compiled binary
rm -f ./cost_parser

# Create/update symlink to latest CSV file
if [ -f "$CSV_FILE" ]; then
    ln -sf "$(basename "$CSV_FILE")" "$LATEST_CSV"
    echo -e "${GREEN}üîó Updated $LATEST_CSV to point to latest cost file${NC}"
fi

echo -e "${GREEN}‚úÖ Cost tracking completed successfully!${NC}"
echo -e "${YELLOW}üìÅ Files created:${NC}"
echo -e "   - $CSV_FILE (timestamped)"
echo -e "   - $LATEST_CSV (always points to latest)"

</file_content>

{"tool":"newFileCreated","path":"batch_update_all_costs.sh","content":"#!/bin/bash

# Batch update all task costs with new CSV structure
# This script processes all existing Cline tasks and generates new CSV files

set -e

# Configuration
CLINE_TASKS_DIR="/Users/emma/Library/Application Support/Code/User/globalStorage/saoudrizwan.claude-dev/tasks"
LOGS_DIR="logs"

# Colors for output
RED='\033[0;31m'
GREEN='\033[0;32m'
YELLOW='\033[1;33m'
BLUE='\033[0;34m'
NC='\033[0m' # No Color

echo -e "${BLUE}üìä Batch Cost Update - Processing all tasks with new CSV structure...${NC}"

# Create logs directory if it doesn't exist
mkdir -p "$LOGS_DIR"

# Compile the cost parser
echo -e "${YELLOW}üîß Compiling cost parser...${NC}"
cd tools/cost-parser
go build -o ../../cost_parser main.go
cd ../..

if [ ! -f "./cost_parser" ]; then
    echo -e "${RED}‚ùå Failed to compile cost parser${NC}"
    exit 1
fi

# Find all task directories
TASK_DIRS=$(ls -1 "$CLINE_TASKS_DIR" | grep '^[0-9]' | sort -n)

if [ -z "$TASK_DIRS" ]; then
    echo -e "${RED}‚ùå No task directories found in $CLINE_TASKS_DIR${NC}"
    exit 1
fi

TOTAL_TASKS=$(echo "$TASK_DIRS" | wc -l)
PROCESSED=0
SUCCESSFUL=0
FAILED=0

echo -e "${BLUE}üìÅ Found $TOTAL_TASKS tasks to process${NC}"

# Process each task
for TASK_ID in $TASK_DIRS; do
    PROCESSED=$((PROCESSED + 1))
    
    # Extract task start time from directory name (timestamp in milliseconds)
    TASK_TIMESTAMP_MS="$TASK_ID"
    TASK_TIMESTAMP_S=$((TASK_TIMESTAMP_MS / 1000))
    
    # Convert to readable format for filename
    DATETIME=$(date -r "$TASK_TIMESTAMP_S" +"%Y-%m-%d_%H-%M-%S")
    
    # Set up file paths
    UI_MESSAGES_FILE="$CLINE_TASKS_DIR/$TASK_ID/ui_messages.json"
    OUTPUT_CSV="$LOGS_DIR/task_${TASK_ID}_${DATETIME}_costs.csv"
    
    echo -e "${YELLOW}[$PROCESSED/$TOTAL_TASKS] Processing task $TASK_ID ($DATETIME)...${NC}"
    
    # Check if ui_messages.json exists
    if [ ! -f "$UI_MESSAGES_FILE" ]; then
        echo -e "${RED}   ‚ùå ui_messages.json not found, skipping${NC}"
        FAILED=$((FAILED + 1))
        continue
    fi
    
    # Run the cost extractor
    if ./cost_parser "$UI_MESSAGES_FILE" "$OUTPUT_CSV" 2>/dev/null; then
        echo -e "${GREEN}   ‚úÖ Successfully created $OUTPUT_CSV${NC}"
        SUCCESSFUL=$((SUCCESSFUL + 1))
    else
        echo -e "${RED}   ‚ùå Failed to process task $TASK_ID${NC}"
        FAILED=$((FAILED + 1))
    fi
done

# Clean up compiled binary
rm -f ./cost_parser

# Summary
echo -e "\n${BLUE}üìä Batch processing completed!${NC}"
echo -e "${GREEN}‚úÖ Successful: $SUCCESSFUL tasks${NC}"
echo -e "${RED}‚ùå Failed: $FAILED tasks${NC}"
echo -e "${YELLOW}üìÅ Total processed: $PROCESSED tasks${NC}"

if [ $SUCCESSFUL -gt 0 ]; then
    echo -e "\n${GREEN}üéâ All CSV files have been updated with the new structure:${NC}"
    echo -e "   - Request Summary, Ask/Say, Text, Cost, Timestamp, Context tokens used, Total cost, [existing columns]"
    echo -e "\n${YELLOW}üìÅ Files are located in: $LOGS_DIR/task_*_costs.csv${NC}"
fi","operationIsLocatedInWorkspace":true}

Result:\n\n## Creating an MCP Server\n\nWhen creating MCP servers, it's important to understand that they operate in a non-interactive environment. The server cannot initiate OAuth flows, open browser windows, or prompt for user input during runtime. All credentials and authentication tokens must be provided upfront through environment variables in the MCP settings configuration. For example, Spotify's API uses OAuth to get a refresh token for the user, but the MCP server cannot initiate this flow. While you can walk the user through obtaining an application client ID and secret, you may have to create a separate one-time setup script (like get-refresh-token.js) that captures and logs the final piece of the puzzle: the user's refresh token (i.e. you might run the script using execute_command which would open a browser for authentication, and then log the refresh token so that you can see it in the command output for you to use in the MCP settings configuration).\n\nUnless the user specifies otherwise, new MCP servers should be created in: /Users/renatamaldaner/Documents/Cline/MCP\n\n### Example MCP Server\n\nFor example, if the user wanted to give you the ability to retrieve weather information, you could create an MCP server that uses the OpenWeather API to get weather information, add it to the MCP settings configuration file, and then notice that you now have access to new tools and resources in the system prompt that you might use to show the user your new capabilities.\n\nThe following example demonstrates how to build an MCP server that provides weather data functionality. While this example shows how to implement resources, resource templates, and tools, in practice you should prefer using tools since they are more flexible and can handle dynamic parameters. The resource and resource template implementations are included here mainly for demonstration purposes of the different MCP capabilities, but a real weather server would likely just expose tools for fetching weather data. (The following steps are for macOS)\n\n1. Use the `create-typescript-server` tool to bootstrap a new project in the default MCP servers directory:\n\n```bash\ncd /Users/renatamaldaner/Documents/Cline/MCP\nnpx @modelcontextprotocol/create-server weather-server\ncd weather-server\n# Install dependencies\nnpm install axios\n```\n\nThis will create a new project with the following structure:\n\n```\nweather-server/\n  ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ package.json\n      {\n        ...\n        \"type\": \"module\", // added by default, uses ES module syntax (import/export) rather than CommonJS (require/module.exports) (Important to know if you create additional scripts in this server repository like a get-refresh-token.js script)\n        \"scripts\": {\n          \"build\": \"tsc && node -e \"require('fs').chmodSync('build/index.js', '755')\"\",\n          ...\n        }\n        ...\n      }\n  ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ tsconfig.json\n  ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ src/\n      ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ weather-server/\n          ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ index.ts      # Main server implementation\n```\n\n2. Replace `src/index.ts` with the following:\n\n```typescript\n#!/usr/bin/env node\nimport { Server } from '@modelcontextprotocol/sdk/server/index.js';\nimport { StdioServerTransport } from '@modelcontextprotocol/sdk/server/stdio.js';\nimport {\n  CallToolRequestSchema,\n  ErrorCode,\n  ListResourcesRequestSchema,\n  ListResourceTemplatesRequestSchema,\n  ListToolsRequestSchema,\n  McpError,\n  ReadResourceRequestSchema,\n} from '@modelcontextprotocol/sdk/types.js';\nimport axios from 'axios';\n\nconst API_KEY = process.env.OPENWEATHER_API_KEY; // provided by MCP config\nif (!API_KEY) {\n  throw new Error('OPENWEATHER_API_KEY environment variable is required');\n}\n\ninterface OpenWeatherResponse {\n  main: {\n    temp: number;\n    humidity: number;\n  };\n  weather: [{ description: string }];\n  wind: { speed: number };\n  dt_txt?: string;\n}\n\nconst isValidForecastArgs = (\n  args: any\n): args is { city: string; days?: number } =>\n  typeof args === 'object' &&\n  args !== null &&\n  typeof args.city === 'string' &&\n  (args.days === undefined || typeof args.days === 'number');\n\nclass WeatherServer {\n  private server: Server;\n  private axiosInstance;\n\n  constructor() {\n    this.server = new Server(\n      {\n        name: 'example-weather-server',\n        version: '0.1.0',\n      },\n      {\n        capabilities: {\n          resources: {},\n          tools: {},\n        },\n      }\n    );\n\n    this.axiosInstance = axios.create({\n      baseURL: 'http://api.openweathermap.org/data/2.5',\n      params: {\n        appid: API_KEY,\n        units: 'metric',\n      },\n    });\n\n    this.setupResourceHandlers();\n    this.setupToolHandlers();\n    \n    // Error handling\n    this.server.onerror = (error) => console.error('[MCP Error]', error);\n    process.on('SIGINT', async () => {\n      await this.server.close();\n      process.exit(0);\n    });\n  }\n\n  // MCP Resources represent any kind of UTF-8 encoded data that an MCP server wants to make available to clients, such as database records, API responses, log files, and more. Servers define direct resources with a static URI or dynamic resources with a URI template that follows the format `[protocol]://[host]/[path]`.\n  private setupResourceHandlers() {\n    // For static resources, servers can expose a list of resources:\n    this.server.setRequestHandler(ListResourcesRequestSchema, async () => ({\n      resources: [\n        // This is a poor example since you could use the resource template to get the same information but this demonstrates how to define a static resource\n        {\n          uri: `weather://San Francisco/current`, // Unique identifier for San Francisco weather resource\n          name: `Current weather in San Francisco`, // Human-readable name\n          mimeType: 'application/json', // Optional MIME type\n          // Optional description\n          description:\n            'Real-time weather data for San Francisco including temperature, conditions, humidity, and wind speed',\n        },\n      ],\n    }));\n\n    // For dynamic resources, servers can expose resource templates:\n    this.server.setRequestHandler(\n      ListResourceTemplatesRequestSchema,\n      async () => ({\n        resourceTemplates: [\n          {\n            uriTemplate: 'weather://{city}/current', // URI template (RFC 6570)\n            name: 'Current weather for a given city', // Human-readable name\n            mimeType: 'application/json', // Optional MIME type\n            description: 'Real-time weather data for a specified city', // Optional description\n          },\n        ],\n      })\n    );\n\n    // ReadResourceRequestSchema is used for both static resources and dynamic resource templates\n    this.server.setRequestHandler(\n      ReadResourceRequestSchema,\n      async (request) => {\n        const match = request.params.uri.match(\n          /^weather://([^/]+)/current$/\n        );\n        if (!match) {\n          throw new McpError(\n            ErrorCode.InvalidRequest,\n            `Invalid URI format: ${request.params.uri}`\n          );\n        }\n        const city = decodeURIComponent(match[1]);\n\n        try {\n          const response = await this.axiosInstance.get(\n            'weather', // current weather\n            {\n              params: { q: city },\n            }\n          );\n\n          return {\n            contents: [\n              {\n                uri: request.params.uri,\n                mimeType: 'application/json',\n                text: JSON.stringify(\n                  {\n                    temperature: response.data.main.temp,\n                    conditions: response.data.weather[0].description,\n                    humidity: response.data.main.humidity,\n                    wind_speed: response.data.wind.speed,\n                    timestamp: new Date().toISOString(),\n                  },\n                  null,\n                  2\n                ),\n              },\n            ],\n          };\n        } catch (error) {\n          if (axios.isAxiosError(error)) {\n            throw new McpError(\n              ErrorCode.InternalError,\n              `Weather API error: ${\n                error.response?.data.message ?? error.message\n              }`\n            );\n          }\n          throw error;\n        }\n      }\n    );\n  }\n\n  /* MCP Tools enable servers to expose executable functionality to the system. Through these tools, you can interact with external systems, perform computations, and take actions in the real world.\n   * - Like resources, tools are identified by unique names and can include descriptions to guide their usage. However, unlike resources, tools represent dynamic operations that can modify state or interact with external systems.\n   * - While resources and tools are similar, you should prefer to create tools over resources when possible as they provide more flexibility.\n   */\n  private setupToolHandlers() {\n    this.server.setRequestHandler(ListToolsRequestSchema, async () => ({\n      tools: [\n        {\n          name: 'get_forecast', // Unique identifier\n          description: 'Get weather forecast for a city', // Human-readable description\n          inputSchema: {\n            // JSON Schema for parameters\n            type: 'object',\n            properties: {\n              city: {\n                type: 'string',\n                description: 'City name',\n              },\n              days: {\n                type: 'number',\n                description: 'Number of days (1-5)',\n                minimum: 1,\n                maximum: 5,\n              },\n            },\n            required: ['city'], // Array of required property names\n          },\n        },\n      ],\n    }));\n\n    this.server.setRequestHandler(CallToolRequestSchema, async (request) => {\n      if (request.params.name !== 'get_forecast') {\n        throw new McpError(\n          ErrorCode.MethodNotFound,\n          `Unknown tool: ${request.params.name}`\n        );\n      }\n\n      if (!isValidForecastArgs(request.params.arguments)) {\n        throw new McpError(\n          ErrorCode.InvalidParams,\n          'Invalid forecast arguments'\n        );\n      }\n\n      const city = request.params.arguments.city;\n      const days = Math.min(request.params.arguments.days || 3, 5);\n\n      try {\n        const response = await this.axiosInstance.get<{\n          list: OpenWeatherResponse[];\n        }>('forecast', {\n          params: {\n            q: city,\n            cnt: days * 8,\n          },\n        });\n\n        return {\n          content: [\n            {\n              type: 'text',\n              text: JSON.stringify(response.data.list, null, 2),\n            },\n          ],\n        };\n      } catch (error) {\n        if (axios.isAxiosError(error)) {\n          return {\n            content: [\n              {\n                type: 'text',\n                text: `Weather API error: ${\n                  error.response?.data.message ?? error.message\n                }`,\n              },\n            ],\n            isError: true,\n          };\n        }\n        throw error;\n      }\n    });\n  }\n\n  async run() {\n    const transport = new StdioServerTransport();\n    await this.server.connect(transport);\n    console.error('Weather MCP server running on stdio');\n  }\n}\n\nconst server = new WeatherServer();\nserver.run().catch(console.error);\n```\n\n(Remember: This is just an example‚Äìyou may use different dependencies, break the implementation up into multiple files, etc.)\n\n3. Build and compile the executable JavaScript file\n\n```bash\nnpm run build\n```\n\n4. Whenever you need an environment variable such as an API key to configure the MCP server, walk the user through the process of getting the key. For example, they may need to create an account and go to a developer dashboard to generate the key. Provide step-by-step instructions and URLs to make it easy for the user to retrieve the necessary information. While you can walk the user through obtaining an application client ID and secret, you may have to create a separate one-time setup script (like get-refresh-token.js) that captures and logs the final piece of the puzzle: the user's refresh token (i.e. you might run the script using execute_command which would open a browser for authentication, and then log the refresh token so that you can see it in the command output for you to use in the MCP settings configuration).\\n\\nUnless the user specifies otherwise, new MCP servers should be created in: /Users/renatamaldaner/Documents/Cline/MCP\\n\\n### Example MCP Server\\n\\nFor example, if the user wanted to give you the ability to retrieve weather information, you could create an MCP server that uses the OpenWeather API to get weather information, add it to the MCP settings configuration file, and then notice that you now have access to new tools and resources in the system prompt that you might use to show the user your new capabilities.\\n\\nThe following example demonstrates how to build an MCP server that provides weather data functionality. While this example shows how to implement resources, resource templates, and tools, in practice you should prefer using tools since they are more flexible and can handle dynamic parameters. The resource and resource template implementations are included here mainly for demonstration purposes of the different MCP capabilities, but a real weather server would likely just expose tools for fetching weather data. (The following steps are for macOS)\\n\\n1. Use the `create-typescript-server` tool to bootstrap a new project in the default MCP servers directory:\\n\\n```bash\\ncd /Users/renatamaldaner/Documents/Cline/MCP\\nnpx @modelcontextprotocol/create-server weather-server\\ncd weather-server\\n# Install dependencies\\nnpm install axios\\n```\\n\\nThis will create a new project with the following structure:\\n\\n```\\nweather-server/\\n  ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ package.json\\n      {\\n        ...\\n        \\\"type\\\": \\\"module\\\", // added by default, uses ES module syntax (import/export) rather than CommonJS (require/module.exports) (Important to know if you create additional scripts in this server repository like a get-refresh-token.js script)\\n        \\\"scripts\\\": {\\n          \\\"build\\\": \\\"tsc && node -e \\\"require('fs').chmodSync('build/index.js', '755')\\\"\\\",\\n          ...\\n        }\\n        ...\\n      }\\n  ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ tsconfig.json\\n  ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ src/\\n      ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ weather-server/\\n          ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ index.ts      # Main server implementation\\n```\\n\\n2. Replace `src/index.ts` with the following:\\n\\n```typescript\\n#!/usr/bin/env node\\nimport { Server } from '@modelcontextprotocol/sdk/server/index.js';\\nimport { StdioServerTransport } from '@modelcontextprotocol/sdk/server/stdio.js';\\nimport {\\n  CallToolRequestSchema,\\n  ErrorCode,\\n  ListResourcesRequestSchema,\\n  ListResourceTemplatesRequestSchema,\\n  ListToolsRequestSchema,\\n  McpError,\\n  ReadResourceRequestSchema,\\n} from '@modelcontextprotocol/sdk/types.js';\\nimport axios from 'axios';\\n\\nconst API_KEY = process.env.OPENWEATHER_API_KEY; days?: number } =>\\n  typeof args === 'object' &&\\n  args !== null &&\\n  typeof args.city === 'string' &&\\n  (args.days === undefined || typeof args.days === 'number');\\n\\nclass WeatherServer {\\n  private server: Server;\\n  private axiosInstance;\\n\\n  constructor() {\\n    this.server = new Server(\\n      {\\n        name: 'example-weather-server',\\n        version: '0.1.0',\\n      },\\n      {\\n        capabilities: {\\n          resources: {},\\n          tools: {},\\n        },\\n      }\\n    );\\n\\n    this.axiosInstance = axios.create({\\n      baseURL: 'http://api.openweathermap.org/data/2.5',\\n      params: {\\n        appid: API_KEY,\\n        units: 'metric',\\n      },\\n    });\\n\\n    this.setupResourceHandlers();\\n    this.setupToolHandlers();\\n    \\n    // Error handling\\n    this.server.onerror = (error) => console.error('[MCP Error]', error);\\n    process.on('SIGINT', async () => {\\n      await this.server.close();\\n      process.exit(0);\\n    });\\n  }\\n\\n  // MCP Resources represent any kind of UTF-8 encoded data that an MCP server wants to make available to clients, such as database records, API responses, log files, and more. Servers define direct resources with a static URI or dynamic resources with a URI template that follows the format `[protocol]://[host]/[path]`.\\n  private setupResourceHandlers() {\\n    // For resourceTemplates: [\\n          {\\n            uriTemplate: 'weather://{city}/current', // URI template (RFC 6570)\\n            name: 'Current weather for a given city', // Human-readable name\\n });\\n\\n        return {\\n          content: [\\n            {\\n              type: 'text',\\n              text: JSON.stringify(response.data.list, null, 2),\\n            },\\n          ],\\n {"request":"[execute_command for '#!/bin/bash

# Temporary batch update script - will be deleted after use
CLINE_TASKS_DIR="/Users/emma/Library/Application Support/Code/User/globalStorage/saoudrizwan.claude-dev/tasks"
LOGS_DIR="logs"

echo "üìä Batch updating all tasks with new CSV structure..."

# Compile the cost parser
cd tools/cost-parser
go build -o ../../cost_parser main.go
cd ../..

# Find all task directories
TASK_DIRS=$(ls -1 "$CLINE_TASKS_DIR" | grep '^[0-9]' | sort -n)
TOTAL_TASKS=$(echo "$TASK_DIRS" | wc -l)
PROCESSED=0

echo "üìÅ Found $TOTAL_TASKS tasks to process"

# Process each task
for TASK_ID in $TASK_DIRS; do
    PROCESSED=$((PROCESSED + 1))
    
    # Extract task start time from directory name (timestamp in milliseconds)
    TASK_TIMESTAMP_MS="$TASK_ID"
    TASK_TIMESTAMP_S=$((TASK_TIMESTAMP_MS / 1000))
    
    # Convert to readable format for filename (matching task start time)
    DATETIME=$(date -r "$TASK_TIMESTAMP_S" +"%Y-%m-%d_%H-%M-%S")
    
    # Set up file paths
    UI_MESSAGES_FILE="$CLINE_TASKS_DIR/$TASK_ID/ui_messages.json"
    OUTPUT_CSV="$LOGS_DIR/task_${TASK_ID}_${DATETIME}_costs.csv"
    
    echo "[$PROCESSED/$TOTAL_TASKS] Processing task $TASK_ID ($DATETIME)..."
    
    # Check if ui_messages.json exists
    if [ -f "$UI_MESSAGES_FILE" ]; then
        # Run the cost extractor
        if ./cost_parser "$UI_MESSAGES_FILE" "$OUTPUT_CSV" 2>/dev/null; then
            echo "   ‚úÖ Successfully created $OUTPUT_CSV"
        else
            echo "   ‚ùå Failed to process task $TASK_ID"
        fi
    else
        echo "   ‚ùå ui_messages.json not found, skipping"
    fi
done

# Clean up compiled binary
rm -f ./cost_parser

Result:\\n\\n## Creating an MCP Server\\n\\nWhen creating MCP servers, it's important to understand that they operate in a non-interactive environment. The server cannot initiate OAuth flows, open browser windows, or prompt for user input during runtime. All credentials and authentication tokens must be provided upfront through environment variables in the MCP settings configuration. For example, Spotify's API uses OAuth to get a refresh token for the user, but the MCP server cannot initiate this flow. While you can walk the user through obtaining an application client ID and secret, you may have to create a separate one-time setup script (like get-refresh-token.js) that captures and logs the final piece of the puzzle: the user's refresh token (i.e. you might run the script using execute_command which would open a browser for authentication, and then log the refresh token so that you can see it in the command output for you to use in the MCP settings configuration).\\n\\nUnless the user specifies otherwise, new MCP servers should be created in: /Users/renatamaldaner/Documents/Cline/MCP\\n\\n### Example MCP Server\\n\\nFor example, if the user wanted to give you the ability to retrieve weather information, you could create an MCP server that uses the OpenWeather API to get weather information, add it to the MCP settings configuration file, and then notice that you now have access to new tools and resources in the system prompt that you might use to show the user your new capabilities.\\n\\nThe following example demonstrates how to build an MCP server that provides weather data functionality. While this example shows how to implement resources, resource templates, and tools, in practice you should prefer using tools since they are more flexible and can handle dynamic parameters. The resource and resource template implementations are included here mainly for demonstration purposes of the different MCP capabilities, but a real weather server would likely just expose tools for fetching weather data. (The following steps are for macOS)\\n\\n1. Use the `create-typescript-server` tool to bootstrap a new project in the default MCP servers directory:\\n\\n```bash\\ncd /Users/renatamaldaner/Documents/Cline/MCP\\nnpx @modelcontextprotocol/create-server weather-server\\ncd weather-server\\n# Install dependencies\\nnpm install axios\\n```\\n\\nThis will create a new project with the following structure:\\n\\n```\\nweather-server/\\n  ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ package.json\\n      {\\n        ...\\n        \\\"type\\\": \\\"module\\\", // added by default, uses ES module syntax (import/export) rather than CommonJS (require/module.exports) (Important to know if you create additional scripts in this server repository like a get-refresh-token.js script)\\n        \\\"scripts\\\": {\\n          \\\"build\\\": \\\"tsc && node -e \\\"require('fs').chmodSync('build/index.js', '755')\\\"\\\",\\n          ...\\n        }\\n        ...\\n      }\\n  ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ tsconfig.json\\n  ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ src/\\n      ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ weather-server/\\n          ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ index.ts      # Main server implementation\\n```\\n\\n2. Replace `src/index.ts` with the following:\\n\\n```typescript\\n#!/usr/bin/env node\\nimport { Server } from '@modelcontextprotocol/sdk/server/index.js';\\nimport { StdioServerTransport } from '@modelcontextprotocol/sdk/server/stdio.js';\\nimport {\\n  CallToolRequestSchema,\\n  ErrorCode,\\n  ListResourcesRequestSchema,\\n  ListResourceTemplatesRequestSchema,\\n  ListToolsRequestSchema,\\n  McpError,\\n  ReadResourceRequestSchema,\\n} from '@modelcontextprotocol/sdk/types.js';\\nimport axios from 'axios';\\n\\nconst API_KEY = process.env.OPENWEATHER_API_KEY; // provided by MCP config\\nif (!API_KEY) {\\n  throw new Error('OPENWEATHER_API_KEY environment variable is required');\\n}\\n\\ninterface OpenWeatherResponse {\\n  main: {\\n    temp: number;\\n    humidity: number;\\n  };\\n  weather: [{ description: string }];\\n  wind: { speed: number };\\n  dt_txt?: string;\\n}\\n\\nconst isValidForecastArgs = (\\n  args: any\\n): args is { city: string; days?: number } =>\\n  typeof args === 'object' &&\\n  args !== null &&\\n  typeof args.city === 'string' &&\\n  (args.days === undefined || typeof args.days === 'number');\\n\\nclass WeatherServer {\\n  private server: Server;\\n  private axiosInstance;\\n\\n  constructor() {\\n    this.server = new Server(\\n      {\\n        name: 'example-weather-server',\\n        version: '0.1.0',\\n      },\\n      {\\n        capabilities: {\\n          resources: {},\\n          tools: {},\\n        },\\n      }\\n    );\\n\\n    this.axiosInstance = axios.create({\\n      baseURL: 'http://api.openweathermap.org/data/2.5',\\n      params: {\\n        appid: API_KEY,\\n        units: 'metric',\\n      },\\n    });\\n\\n    this.setupResourceHandlers();\\n    this.setupToolHandlers();\\n    \\n    // Error handling\\n    this.server.onerror = (error) => console.error('[MCP Error]', error);\\n    process.on('SIGINT', async () => {\\n      await this.server.close();\\n      process.exit(0);\\n    });\\n  }\\n\\n  // MCP Resources represent any kind of UTF-8 encoded data that an MCP server wants to make available to clients, such as database records, API responses, log files, and more. Servers define direct resources with a static URI or dynamic resources with a URI template that follows the format `[protocol]://[host]/[path]`.\\n  private setupResourceHandlers() {\\n    // For static resources, servers can expose a list of resources:\\n    this.server.setRequestHandler(ListResourcesRequestSchema, async () => ({\\n      resources: [\\n        // This is a poor example since you could use the resource template to get the same information but this demonstrates how to define a static resource\\n        {\\n          uri: `weather://San Francisco/current`, // Unique identifier for San Francisco weather resource\\n          name: `Current weather in San Francisco`, // Human-readable name\\n          mimeType: 'application/json', // Optional MIME type\\n          // Optional description\\n          description:\\n            'Real-time weather data for San Francisco including temperature, conditions, humidity, and wind speed',\\n        },\\n      ],\\n    }));\\n\\n    // For dynamic resources, servers can expose resource templates:\\n    this.server.setRequestHandler(\\n      ListResourceTemplatesRequestSchema,\\n      async () => ({\\n        resourceTemplates: [\\n          {\\n            uriTemplate: 'weather://{city}/current', // URI template (RFC 6570)\\n            name: 'Current weather for a given city', // Human-readable name\\n            mimeType: 'application/json', // Optional MIME type\\n            description: 'Real-time weather data for a specified city', // Optional description\\n          },\\n        ],\\n      })\\n    );\\n\\n    // ReadResourceRequestSchema is used for both static resources and dynamic resource templates\\n    this.server.setRequestHandler(\\n      ReadResourceRequestSchema,\\n      async (request) => {\\n        const match = request.params.uri.match(\\n          /^weather://([^/]+)/current$/\\n        );\\n        if (!match) {\\n          throw new McpError(\\n            ErrorCode.InvalidRequest,\\n            `Invalid URI format: ${request.params.uri}`\\n          );\\n        }\\n        const city = decodeURIComponent(match[1]);\\n\\n        try {\\n          const response = await this.axiosInstance.get(\\n            'weather', // current weather\\n            {\\n              params: { q: city },\\n            }\\n          );\\n\\n          return {\\n            contents: [\\n              {\\n                uri: request.params.uri,\\n                mimeType: 'application/json',\\n                text: JSON.stringify(\\n                  {\\n                    temperature: response.data.main.temp,\\n                    conditions: response.data.weather[0].description,\\n                    humidity: response.data.main.humidity,\\n                    wind_speed: response.data.wind.speed,\\n                    timestamp: new Date().toISOString(),\\n                  },\\n                  null,\\n                  2\\n                ),\\n              },\\n            ],\\n          };\\n        } catch (error) {\\n          if (axios.isAxiosError(error)) {\\n            throw new McpError(\\n              ErrorCode.InternalError,\\n              `Weather API error: ${\\n                error.response?.data.message ?? error.message\\n              }`\\n            );\\n          }\\n          throw error;\\n        }\\n      }\\n    );\\n  }\\n\\n  /* MCP Tools enable servers to expose executable functionality to the system. Through these tools, you can interact with external systems, perform computations, and take actions in the real world.\\n   * - Like resources, tools are identified by unique names and can include descriptions to guide their usage. However, unlike resources, tools represent dynamic operations that can modify state or interact with external systems.\\n   * - While resources and tools are similar, you should prefer to create tools over resources when possible as they provide more flexibility.\\n   */\\n  private setupToolHandlers() {\\n    this.server.setRequestHandler(ListToolsRequestSchema, async () => ({\\n      tools: [\\n        {\\n          name: 'get_forecast', // Unique identifier\\n          description: 'Get weather forecast for a city', // Human-readable description\\n          inputSchema: {\\n            // JSON Schema for parameters\\n            type: 'object',\\n            properties: {\\n              city: {\\n                type: 'string',\\n                description: 'City name',\\n              },\\n              days: {\\n                type: 'number',\\n                description: 'Number of days (1-5)',\\n                minimum: 1,\\n                maximum: 5,\\n              },\\n            },\\n            required: ['city'], // Array of required property names\\n          },\\n        },\\n      ],\\n    }));\\n\\n    this.server.setRequestHandler(CallToolRequestSchema, async (request) => {\\n      if (request.params.name !== 'get_forecast') {\\n        throw new McpError(\\n          ErrorCode.MethodNotFound,\\n          `Unknown tool: ${request.params.name}`\\n        );\\n      }\\n\\n      if (!isValidForecastArgs(request.params.arguments)) {\\n        throw new McpError(\\n          ErrorCode.InvalidParams,\\n          'Invalid forecast arguments'\\n        );\\n      }\\n\\n      const city = request.params.arguments.city;\\n      const days = Math.min(request.params.arguments.days || 3, 5);\\n\\n      try {\\n        const response = await this.axiosInstance.get<{\\n          list: OpenWeatherResponse[];\\n        }>('forecast', {\\n          params: {\\n            q: city,\\n            cnt: days * 8,\\n          },\\n        });\\n\\n        return {\\n          content: [\\n            {\\n              type: 'text',\\n              text: JSON.stringify(response.data.list, null, 2),\\n            },\\n          ],\\n        };\\n      } catch (error) {\\n        if (axios.isAxiosError(error)) {\\n          return {\\n            content: [\\n              {\\n                type: 'text',\\n                text: `Weather API error: ${\\n                  error.response?.data.message ?? error.message\\n                }`,\\n              },\\n            ],\\n            isError: true,\\n          };\\n        }\\n        throw error;\\n      }\\n    });\\n  }\\n\\n  async run() {\\n    const transport = new StdioServerTransport();\\n    await this.server.connect(transport);\\n    console.error('Weather MCP server running on stdio');\\n  }\\n}\\n\\nconst server = new WeatherServer();\\nserver.run().catch(console.error);\\n```\\n\\n(Remember: This is just an example‚Äìyou may use different dependencies, break the implementation up into multiple files, etc.)\\n\\n3. Build and compile the executable JavaScript file\\n\\n```bash\\nnpm run build\\n```\\n\\n4. Whenever you need an environment variable such as an API key to configure the MCP server, walk the user through the process of getting the key. For example, they may need to create an account and go to a developer dashboard to generate the key. Provide step-by-step instructions and URLs to make it easy for the user to retrieve the necessary information. Then use the ask_followup_question tool to ask the user for the key, in this case the OpenWeather API key.\\n\\n5. Install the MCP Server by adding the MCP server configuration to the settings file located at '/Users/renatamaldaner/Library/Application Support/Code/User/globalStorage/saoudrizwan.claude-dev/settings/cline_mcp_settings.json'. The settings file may have other MCP servers already configured, so you would read it first and then add your new server to the existing `mcpServers` object.\\n\\nIMPORTANT: Regardless of what else you see in the MCP settings file, you must default any new MCP servers you create to disabled=false and autoApprove=[].\\n\\n```json\\n{\\n  \\\"mcpServers\\\": {\\n    ...,\\n    \\\"weather\\\": {\\n      \\\"command\\\": \\\"node\\\",\\n      \\\"args\\\": [\\\"/path/to/weather-server/build/index.js\\\"],\\n      \\\"env\\\": {\\n        \\\"OPENWEATHER_API_KEY\\\": \\\"user-provided-api-key\\\"\\n      }\\n    },\\n  }\\n}\\n```\\n\\n(Note: the user may also ask you to install the MCP server to the Claude desktop app, in which case you would read then modify `~/Library/Application Support/Claude/claude_desktop_config.json` on macOS for example. It follows the same format of a top level `mcpServers` object.)\\n\\n6. After you have edited the MCP settings configuration file, the system will automatically run all the servers and expose the available tools and resources in the 'Connected MCP Servers' section. (Note: If you encounter a 'not connected' error when testing a newly installed mcp server, a common cause is an incorrect build path in your MCP settings configuration. Since compiled JavaScript files are commonly output to either 'dist/' or 'build/' directories, double-check that the build path in your MCP settings matches where your files are actually being compiled. E.g. If you assumed 'build' as the folder, check tsconfig.json to see if it's using 'dist' instead.)\\n\\n7. Now that you have access to these new tools and resources, you may suggest ways the user can command you to invoke them - for example, with this new weather tool now available, you can invite the user to ask \\\"what's the weather in San Francisco?\\\"\\n\\n## Editing MCP Servers\\n\\nThe user may ask to add tools or resources that may make sense to add to an existing MCP server (listed under 'Connected MCP Servers' below: (None running currently), e.g. if it would use the same API. This would be possible if you can locate the MCP server repository on the user's system by looking at the server arguments for a filepath. You might then use list_files and read_file to explore the files in the repository, and use replace_in_file to make changes to the files.\\n\\nHowever some MCP servers may be running from installed packages rather than a local repository, in which case it may make more sense to create a new MCP server.\\n\\n# MCP Servers Are Not Always Necessary\\n\\nThe user may not always request the use or creation of MCP servers. Instead, they might provide tasks that can be completed with existing tools. for TASK_ID in $TASK_DIRS; do
    PROCESSED=$((PROCESSED + 1))
    
    # Extract task start time from directory name (timestamp in milliseconds)
    TASK_TIMESTAMP_MS="$TASK_ID"
    TASK_TIMESTAMP_S=$((TASK_TIMESTAMP_MS / 1000))
    
    # Convert to readable format for filename (matching task start time)
    DATETIME=$(date -r "$TASK_TIMESTAMP_S" +"%Y-%m-%d_%H-%M-%S")
    
    # Set up file paths
    UI_MESSAGES_FILE="$CLINE_TASKS_DIR/$TASK_ID/ui_messages.json"
    OUTPUT_CSV="$LOGS_DIR/task_${TASK_ID}_${DATETIME}_costs.csv"
    
    echo "[$PROCESSED/$TOTAL_TASKS] Processing task $TASK_ID ($DATETIME)..."
    
    # Check if ui_messages.json exists
    if [ -f "$UI_MESSAGES_FILE" ]; then
        # Run the cost extractor
        if ./cost_parser "$UI_MESSAGES_FILE" "$OUTPUT_CSV" 2>/dev/null; then
            echo "   ‚úÖ Successfully created $OUTPUT_CSV"
        else
            echo "   ‚ùå Failed to process task $TASK_ID"
        fi
    else
        echo "   ‚ùå ui_messages.json not found, skipping"
    fi
done

# Clean up compiled binary
rm -f ./cost_parser

echo "üéâ Batch processing completed!"

Result:\n\n## Creating an MCP Server\n\nWhen creating MCP servers, it's important to understand that they operate in a non-interactive environment. The server cannot initiate OAuth flows, open browser windows, or prompt for user input during runtime. All credentials and authentication tokens must be provided upfront through environment variables in the MCP settings configuration. For example, Spotify's API uses OAuth to get a refresh token for the user, but the MCP server cannot initiate this flow. While you can walk the user through obtaining an application client ID and secret, you may have to create a separate one-time setup script (like get-refresh-token.js) that captures and logs the final piece of the puzzle: the user's refresh token (i.e. you might run the script using execute_command which would open a browser for authentication, and then log the refresh token so that you can see it in the command output for you to use in the MCP settings configuration).\n\nUnless the user specifies otherwise, new MCP servers should be created in: /Users/renatamaldaner/Documents/Cline/MCP\n\n### Example MCP Server\n\nFor example, if the user wanted to give you the ability to retrieve weather information, you could create an MCP server that uses the OpenWeather API to get weather information, add it to the MCP settings configuration file, and then notice that you now have access to new tools and resources in the system prompt that you might use to show the user your new capabilities.\n\nThe following example demonstrates how to build an MCP server that provides weather data functionality. While this example shows how to implement resources, resource templates, and tools, in practice you should prefer using tools since they are more flexible and can handle dynamic parameters. The resource and resource template implementations are included here mainly for demonstration purposes of the different MCP capabilities, but a real weather server would likely just expose tools for fetching weather data. (The following steps are for macOS)\n\n1. Use the `create-typescript-server` tool to bootstrap a new project in the default MCP servers directory:\n\n```bash\ncd /Users/renatamaldaner/Documents/Cline/MCP\nnpx @modelcontextprotocol/create-server weather-server\ncd weather-server\n# Install dependencies\nnpm install axios\n```\n\nThis will create a new project with the following structure:\n\n```\nweather-server/\n  ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ package.json\n      {\n        ...\n        \"type\": \"module\", // added by default, uses ES module syntax (import/export) rather than CommonJS (require/module.exports) (Important to know if you create additional scripts in this server repository like a get-refresh-token.js script)\n        \"scripts\": {\n          \"build\": \"tsc && node -e \"require('fs').chmodSync('build/index.js', '755')\"\",\n          ...\n        }\n        ...\n      }\n  ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ tsconfig.json\n  ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ src/\n      ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ weather-server/\n          ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ index.ts      # Main server implementation\n```\n\n2. Replace `src/index.ts` with the following:\n\n```typescript\n#!/usr/bin/env node\nimport { Server } from '@modelcontextprotocol/sdk/server/index.js';\nimport { StdioServerTransport } from '@modelcontextprotocol/sdk/server/stdio.js';\nimport {\n  CallToolRequestSchema,\n  ErrorCode,\n  ListResourcesRequestSchema,\n  ListResourceTemplatesRequestSchema,\n  ListToolsRequestSchema,\n  McpError,\n  ReadResourceRequestSchema,\n} from '@modelcontextprotocol/sdk/types.js';\nimport axios from 'axios';\n\nconst API_KEY = process.env.OPENWEATHER_API_KEY; // provided by MCP config\nif (!API_KEY) {\n  throw new Error('OPENWEATHER_API_KEY environment variable is required');\n}\n\ninterface OpenWeatherResponse {\n  main: {\n    temp: number;\n    humidity: number;\n  };\n  weather: [{ description: string }];\n  wind: { speed: number };\n  dt_txt?: string;\n}\n\nconst isValidForecastArgs = (\n  args: any\n): args is { city: string; days?: number } =>\n  typeof args === 'object' &&\n  args !== null &&\n  typeof args.city === 'string' &&\n  (args.days === undefined || typeof args.days === 'number');\n\nclass WeatherServer {\n  private server: Server;\n  private axiosInstance;\n\n  constructor() {\n    this.server = new Server(\n      {\n        name: 'example-weather-server',\n        version: '0.1.0',\n      },\n      {\n        capabilities: {\n          resources: {},\n          tools: {},\n        },\n      }\n    );\n\n    this.axiosInstance = axios.create({\n      baseURL: 'http://api.openweathermap.org/data/2.5',\n      params: {\n        appid: API_KEY,\n        units: 'metric',\n      },\n    });\n\n    this.setupResourceHandlers();\n    this.setupToolHandlers();\n    \n    // Error handling\n    this.server.onerror = (error) => console.error('[MCP Error]', error);\n    process.on('SIGINT', async () => {\n      await this.server.close();\n      process.exit(0);\n    });\n  }\n\n  // MCP Resources represent any kind of UTF-8 encoded data that an MCP server wants to make available to clients, such as database records, API responses, log files, and more. Servers define direct resources with a static URI or dynamic resources with a URI template that follows the format `[protocol]://[host]/[path]`.\n  private setupResourceHandlers() {\n    // For static resources, servers can expose a list of resources:\n    this.server.setRequestHandler(ListResourcesRequestSchema, async () => ({\n      resources: [\n        // This is a poor example since you could use the resource template to get the same information but this demonstrates how to define a static resource\n        {\n          uri: `weather://San Francisco/current`, // Unique identifier for San Francisco weather resource\n          name: `Current weather in San Francisco`, // Human-readable name\n          mimeType: 'application/json', // Optional MIME type\n          // Optional description\n          description:\n            'Real-time weather data for San Francisco including temperature, conditions, humidity, and wind speed',\n        },\n      ],\n    }));\n\n    // For dynamic resources, servers can expose resource templates:\n    this.server.setRequestHandler(\n      ListResourceTemplatesRequestSchema,\n      async () => ({\n        resourceTemplates: [\n          {\n            uriTemplate: 'weather://{city}/current', // URI template (RFC 6570)\n            name: 'Current weather for a given city', // Human-readable name\n            mimeType: 'application/json', // Optional MIME type\n            description: 'Real-time weather data for a specified city', // Optional description\n          },\n        ],\n      })\n    );\n\n    // ReadResourceRequestSchema is used for both static resources and dynamic resource templates\n    this.server.setRequestHandler(\n      ReadResourceRequestSchema,\n      async (request) => {\n        const match = request.params.uri.match(\n          /^weather://([^/]+)/current$/\n        );\n        if (!match) {\n          throw new McpError(\n            ErrorCode.InvalidRequest,\n            `Invalid URI format: ${request.params.uri}`\n          );\n        }\n        const city = decodeURIComponent(match[1]);\n\n        try {\n          const response = await this.axiosInstance.get(\n All credentials and authentication tokens must be provided upfront through environment variables in the MCP settings configuration. For example, Spotify's API uses OAuth to get a refresh token for the user, but the MCP server cannot initiate this flow. While you can walk the user through obtaining an application client ID and secret, you may have to create a separate one-time setup script (like get-refresh-token.js) that captures and logs the final piece of the puzzle: the user's refresh token (i.e. you might run the script using execute_command which would open a browser for authentication, and then log the refresh token so that you can see it in the command output for you to use in the MCP settings configuration).\\n\\nUnless the user specifies otherwise, new MCP servers should be created in: /Users/renatamaldaner/Documents/Cline/MCP\\n\\n### Example MCP Server\\n\\nFor example, if the user wanted to give you the ability to retrieve weather information, you could create an MCP server that uses the OpenWeather API to get weather information, add it to the MCP settings configuration file, and then notice that you now have access to new tools and resources in the system prompt that you might use to show the user your new capabilities.\\n\\nThe following example demonstrates how to build an MCP server that provides weather data functionality. Result:\\n\\n## Creating an MCP Server\\n\\nWhen creating MCP servers, it's important to understand that they operate in a non-interactive environment. The server cannot initiate OAuth flows, open browser windows, or prompt for user input during runtime. All credentials and authentication tokens must be provided upfront through environment variables in the MCP settings configuration. For example, Spotify's API uses OAuth to get a refresh token for the user, but the MCP server cannot initiate this flow. While you can walk the user through obtaining an application client ID and secret, you may have to create a separate one-time setup script (like get-refresh-token.js) that captures and logs the final piece of the puzzle: the user's refresh token (i.e. you might run the script using execute_command which would open a browser for authentication, and then log the refresh token so that you can see it in the command output for you to use in the MCP settings configuration).\\n\\nUnless the user specifies otherwise, new MCP servers should be created in: /Users/renatamaldaner/Documents/Cline/MCP\\n\\n### Example MCP Server\\n\\nFor example, if the user wanted to give you the ability to retrieve weather information, you could create an MCP server that uses the OpenWeather API to get weather information, add it to the MCP settings configuration file, and then notice that you now have access to new tools and resources in the system prompt that you might use to show the user your new capabilities.\\n\\nThe following example demonstrates how to build an MCP server that provides weather data functionality. While this example shows how to implement resources, resource templates, and tools, in practice you should prefer using tools since they are more flexible and can handle dynamic parameters. The resource and resource template implementations are included here mainly for demonstration purposes of the different MCP capabilities, but a real weather server would likely just expose tools for fetching weather data. (The following steps are for macOS)\\n\\n1. Use the `create-typescript-server` tool to bootstrap a new project in the default MCP servers directory:\\n\\n```bash\\ncd /Users/renatamaldaner/Documents/Cline/MCP\\nnpx @modelcontextprotocol/create-server weather-server\\ncd weather-server\\n# Install dependencies\\nnpm install axios\\n```\\n\\nThis will create a new project with the following structure:\\n\\n```\\nweather-server/\\n  ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ package.json\\n      {\\n        ...\\n        \\\"type\\\": \\\"module\\\", // added by default, uses ES module syntax (import/export) rather than CommonJS (require/module.exports) (Important to know if you create additional scripts in this server repository like a get-refresh-token.js script)\\n        \\\"scripts\\\": {\\n          \\\"build\\\": \\\"tsc && node -e \\\"require('fs').chmodSync('build/index.js', '755')\\\"\\\",\\n          ...\\n        }\\n        ...\\n      }\\n  ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ tsconfig.json\\n  ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ src/\\n      ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ weather-server/\\n          ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ index.ts      # Main server implementation\\n```\\n\\n2. Replace `src/index.ts` with the following:\\n\\n```typescript\\n#!/usr/bin/env node\\nimport { Server } from '@modelcontextprotocol/sdk/server/index.js';\\nimport { StdioServerTransport } from '@modelcontextprotocol/sdk/server/stdio.js';\\nimport {\\n  CallToolRequestSchema,\\n  ErrorCode,\\n  ListResourcesRequestSchema,\\n  ListResourceTemplatesRequestSchema,\\n  ListToolsRequestSchema,\\n  McpError,\\n  ReadResourceRequestSchema,\\n} from '@modelcontextprotocol/sdk/types.js';\\nimport axios from 'axios';\\n\\nconst API_KEY = process.env.OPENWEATHER_API_KEY; // provided by MCP config\\nif (!API_KEY) {\\n  throw new Error('OPENWEATHER_API_KEY environment variable is required');\\n}\\n\\ninterface OpenWeatherResponse {\\n  main: {\\n    temp: number;\\n    humidity: number;\\n  };\\n  weather: [{ description: string }];\\n  wind: { speed: number };\\n  dt_txt?: string;\\n}\\n\\nconst isValidForecastArgs = (\\n  args: any\\n): args is { city: string; days?: number } =>\\n  typeof args === 'object' &&\\n  args !== null &&\\n  typeof args.city === 'string' &&\\n  (args.days === undefined || typeof args.days === 'number');\\n\\nclass WeatherServer {\\n  private server: Server;\\n  private axiosInstance;\\n\\n  constructor() {\\n    this.server = new Server(\\n      {\\n        name: 'example-weather-server',\\n        version: '0.1.0',\\n      },\\n      {\\n        capabilities: {\\n          resources: {},\\n          tools: {},\\n        },\\n      }\\n    );\\n\\n    this.axiosInstance = axios.create({\\n      baseURL: 'http://api.openweathermap.org/data/2.5',\\n      params: {\\n        appid: API_KEY,\\n        units: 'metric',\\n      },\\n    });\\n\\n    this.setupResourceHandlers();\\n    this.setupToolHandlers();\\n    \\n    // Error handling\\n    this.server.onerror = (error) => console.error('[MCP Error]', error);\\n    process.on('SIGINT', async () => {\\n      await this.server.close();\\n      process.exit(0);\\n    });\\n  }\\n\\n  // MCP Resources represent any kind of UTF-8 encoded data that an MCP server wants to make available to clients, such as database records, API responses, log files, and more. Servers define direct resources with a static URI or dynamic resources with a URI template that follows the format `[protocol]://[host]/[path]`.\\n  private setupResourceHandlers() {\\n    // For static resources, servers can expose a list of resources:\\n    this.server.setRequestHandler(ListResourcesRequestSchema, async () => ({\\n      resources: [\\n        // This is a poor example since you could use the resource template to get the same information but this demonstrates how to define a static resource\\n        {\\n          uri: `weather://San Francisco/current`, // Unique identifier for San Francisco weather resource\\n          name: `Current weather in San Francisco`, // Human-readable name\\n          mimeType: 'application/json', // Optional MIME type\\n          // Optional description\\n          description:\\n            'Real-time weather data for San Francisco including temperature, conditions, humidity, and wind speed',\\n        },\\n      ],\\n    }));\\n\\n    // For dynamic resources, servers can expose resource templates:\\n    this.server.setRequestHandler(\\n      ListResourceTemplatesRequestSchema,\\n      async () => ({\\n        resourceTemplates: [\\n          {\\n            uriTemplate: 'weather://{city}/current', // URI template (RFC 6570)\\n            name: 'Current weather for a given city', // Human-readable name\\n            mimeType: 'application/json', // Optional MIME type\\n            description: 'Real-time weather data for a specified city', // Optional description\\n          },\\n        ],\\n      })\\n    );\\n\\n    // ReadResourceRequestSchema is used for both static resources and dynamic resource templates\\n    this.server.setRequestHandler(\\n      ReadResourceRequestSchema,\\n      async (request) => {\\n        const match = request.params.uri.match(\\n          /^weather://([^/]+)/current$/\\n        );\\n        if (!match) {\\n          throw new McpError(\\n            ErrorCode.InvalidRequest,\\n            `Invalid URI format: ${request.params.uri}`\\n          );\\n        }\\n        const city = decodeURIComponent(match[1]);\\n\\n        try {\\n          const response = await this.axiosInstance.get(\\n            'weather', // current weather\\n            {\\n              params: { q: city },\\n            }\\n          );\\n\\n          return {\\n            contents: [\\n              {\\n                uri: request.params.uri,\\n                mimeType: 'application/json',\\n                text: JSON.stringify(\\n                  {\\n                    temperature: response.data.main.temp,\\n                    conditions: response.data.weather[0].description,\\n                    humidity: response.data.main.humidity,\\n                    wind_speed: response.data.wind.speed,\\n                    timestamp: new Date().toISOString(),\\n                  },\\n                  null,\\n                  2\\n                ),\\n              },\\n            ],\\n          };\\n        } catch (error) {\\n          if (axios.isAxiosError(error)) {\\n            throw new McpError(\\n              ErrorCode.InternalError,\\n              `Weather API error: ${\\n                error.response?.data.message ?? error.message\\n              }`\\n            );\\n          }\\n          throw error;\\n        }\\n      }\\n    );\\n  }\\n\\n  /* MCP Tools enable servers to expose executable functionality to the system. Through these tools, you can interact with external systems, perform computations, and take actions in the real world.\\n   * - Like resources, tools are identified by unique names and can include descriptions to guide their usage. However, unlike resources, tools represent dynamic operations that can modify state or interact with external systems.\\n   * - While resources and tools are similar, you should prefer to create tools over resources when possible as they provide more flexibility.\\n   */\\n  private setupToolHandlers() {\\n    this.server.setRequestHandler(ListToolsRequestSchema, async () => ({\\n      tools: [\\n        {\\n          name: 'get_forecast', // Unique identifier\\n          description: 'Get weather forecast for a city', // Human-readable description\\n          inputSchema: {\\n            // JSON Schema for parameters\\n            type: 'object',\\n            properties: {\\n              city: {\\n                type: 'string',\\n                description: 'City name',\\n              },\\n              days: {\\n                type: 'number',\\n                description: 'Number of days (1-5)',\\n                minimum: 1,\\n                maximum: 5,\\n              },\\n            },\\n            required: ['city'], // Array of required property names\\n          },\\n        },\\n      ],\\n    }));\\n\\n    this.server.setRequestHandler(CallToolRequestSchema, async (request) => {\\n      if (request.params.name !== 'get_forecast') {\\n        throw new McpError(\\n          ErrorCode.MethodNotFound,\\n          `Unknown tool: ${request.params.name}`\\n        );\\n      }\\n\\n      if (!isValidForecastArgs(request.params.arguments)) {\\n        throw new McpError(\\n          ErrorCode.InvalidParams,\\n          'Invalid forecast arguments'\\n        );\\n      }\\n\\n      const city = request.params.arguments.city;\\n      const days = Math.min(request.params.arguments.days || 3, 5);\\n\\n      try {\\n        const response = await this.axiosInstance.get<{\\n          list: OpenWeatherResponse[];\\n        }>('forecast', {\\n          params: {\\n            q: city,\\n            cnt: days * 8,\\n          },\\n        });\\n\\n        return {\\n          content: [\\n            {\\n              type: 'text',\\n              text: JSON.stringify(response.data.list, null, 2),\\n            },\\n          ],\\n        };\\n      } catch (error) {\\n        if (axios.isAxiosError(error)) {\\n          return {\\n            content: [\\n              {\\n                type: 'text',\\n                text: `Weather API error: ${\\n                  error.response?.data.message ?? error.message\\n                }`,\\n              },\\n            ],\\n            isError: true,\\n          };\\n        }\\n        throw error;\\n      }\\n    });\\n  }\\n\\n  async run() {\\n    const transport = new StdioServerTransport();\\n    await this.server.connect(transport);\\n    console.error('Weather MCP server running on stdio');\\n  }\\n}\\n\\nconst server = new WeatherServer();\\nserver.run().catch(console.error);\\n```\\n\\n(Remember: This is just an example‚Äìyou may use different dependencies, break the implementation up into multiple files, etc.)\\n\\n3. Build and compile the executable JavaScript file\\n\\n```bash\\nnpm run build\\n```\\n\\n4. Whenever you need an environment variable such as an API key to configure the MCP server, walk the user through the process of getting the key. For example, they may need to create an account and go to a developer dashboard to generate the key. Provide step-by-step instructions and URLs to make it easy for the user to retrieve the necessary information. Then use the ask_followup_question tool to ask the user for the key, in this case the OpenWeather API key.\\n\\n5. Install the MCP Server by adding the MCP server configuration to the settings file located at '/Users/renatamaldaner/Library/Application Support/Code/User/globalStorage/saoudrizwan.claude-dev/settings/cline_mcp_settings.json'. The settings file may have other MCP servers already configured, so you would read it first and then add your new server to the existing `mcpServers` object.\\n\\nIMPORTANT: Regardless of what else you see in the MCP settings file, you must default any new MCP servers you create to disabled=false and autoApprove=[].\\n\\n```json\\n{\\n  \\\"mcpServers\\\": {\\n    ...,\\n    \\\"weather\\\": {\\n      \\\"command\\\": \\\"node\\\",\\n      \\\"args\\\": [\\\"/path/to/weather-server/build/index.js\\\"],\\n      \\\"env\\\": {\\n        \\\"OPENWEATHER_API_KEY\\\": \\\"user-provided-api-key\\\"\\n      }\\n    },\\n  }\\n}\\n```\\n\\n(Note: the user may also ask you to install the MCP server to the Claude desktop app, in which case you would read then modify `~/Library/Application Support/Claude/claude_desktop_config.json` on macOS for example. It follows the same format of a top level `mcpServers` object.)\\n\\n6. After you have edited the MCP settings configuration file, the system will automatically run all the servers and expose the available tools and resources in the 'Connected MCP Servers' section. (Note: If you encounter a 'not connected' error when testing a newly installed mcp server, a common cause is an incorrect build path in your MCP settings configuration. Since compiled JavaScript files are commonly output to either 'dist/' or 'build/' directories, double-check that the build path in your MCP settings matches where your files are actually being compiled. E.g. If you assumed 'build' as the folder, check tsconfig.json to see if it's using 'dist' instead.)\\n\\n7. Now that you have access to these new tools and resources, you may suggest ways the user can command you to invoke them - for example, with this new weather tool now available, you can invite the user to ask \\\"what's the weather in San Francisco?\\\"\\n\\n## Editing MCP Servers\\n\\nThe user may ask to add tools or resources that may make sense to add to an existing MCP server (listed under 'Connected MCP Servers' below: (None running currently), e.g. if it would use the same API. This would be possible if you can locate the MCP server repository on the user's system by looking at the server arguments for a filepath. You might then use list_files and read_file to explore the files in the repository, and use replace_in_file to make changes to the files.\\n\\nHowever some MCP servers may be running from installed packages rather than a local repository, in which case it may make more sense to create a new MCP server.\\n\\n# MCP Servers Are Not Always Necessary\\n\\nThe user may not always request the use or creation of MCP servers. Instead, they might provide tasks that can be completed with existing tools. package main

import (
	"encoding/csv"
	"encoding/json"
	"fmt"
	"io/ioutil"
	"log"
	"os"
	"regexp"
	"sort"
	"strconv"
	"strings"
	"time"
)

// UIMessage represents a message from Cline's UI messages JSON
type UIMessage struct {
	TS   int64  `json:"ts"`
	Type string `json:"type"`
	Say  string `json:"say,omitempty"`
	Text string `json:"text,omitempty"`
}

// APIRequestData represents the parsed API request data from UI messages
type APIRequestData struct {
	Request     string  `json:"request"`
	Cost        float64 `json:"cost"`
	TokensIn    int     `json:"tokensIn"`
	TokensOut   int     `json:"tokensOut"`
	CacheWrites int     `json:"cacheWrites"`
	CacheReads  int     `json:"cacheReads"`
}

// CostEntry represents a single cost tracking entry
type CostEntry struct {
	RequestSummary         string
	AskSay                 string
	Text                   string
	RequestCost            float64
	Timestamp              string
	ContextTokensUsed      int
	TotalCost              float64
	UserRequest            string
	ClineAction            string
	ToolUsed               string
	HasImages              string
	Phase                  string
	ContextPercentage      string
	SearchTermInTranscript string
	CostNotes              string
	TimeApprox             string
}

func main() {
	if len(os.Args) != 3 {
		log.Fatal("Usage: cost_extractor <ui_messages.json> <output.csv>")
	}

	uiMessagesFile := os.Args[1]
	csvFile := os.Args[2]

	// Read and parse ui_messages.json
	data, err := ioutil.ReadFile(uiMessagesFile)
	if err != nil {
		log.Fatalf("‚ùå Error reading ui_messages.json: %v", err)
	}

	var messages []UIMessage
	if err := json.Unmarshal(data, &messages); err != nil {
		log.Fatalf("‚ùå Error parsing JSON: %v", err)
	}

	// Extract API costs and build context from user messages
	var apiCosts []CostEntry
	var totalCost float64
	requestCounter := 1

	// Build a map of user messages for context
	userMessages := make(map[int64]string)
	clineResponses := make(map[int64]string)

	// Build a map of different types of user interactions
	var mainUserRequest string
	var userFeedbacks []string

	for _, msg := range messages {
		if msg.Type == "say" && msg.Say == "text" && msg.Text != "" {
			// This is the actual user request that started the task
			if mainUserRequest == "" {
				mainUserRequest = msg.Text
			}
		} else if msg.Type == "say" && msg.Say == "user_feedback" && msg.Text != "" {
			// Collect user feedback messages
			userFeedbacks = append(userFeedbacks, msg.Text)
		} else if msg.Type == "ask" && msg.Text != "" {
			// Extract the actual user request text (not lowercased, preserve original)
			userText := msg.Text
			// Keep more context but clean it up
			if len(userText) > 200 {
				userText = userText[:200] + "..."
			}
			// Clean up newlines and extra spaces
			userText = strings.ReplaceAll(userText, "\n", " ")
			userText = strings.ReplaceAll(userText, "\t", " ")
			// Remove multiple spaces
			userText = regexp.MustCompile(`\s+`).ReplaceAllString(userText, " ")
			userText = strings.TrimSpace(userText)
			userMessages[msg.TS] = userText
		} else if msg.Type == "say" && msg.Say == "text" && msg.Text != "" {
			// Extract Cline's responses for determining what Cline actually did
			responseText := msg.Text
			if len(responseText) > 150 {
				responseText = responseText[:150] + "..."
			}
			clineResponses[msg.TS] = responseText
		}
	}

	// Process all messages to create entries with new structure
	isFirstEntry := true
	for _, msg := range messages {
		timestamp := time.Unix(msg.TS/1000, (msg.TS%1000)*1000000)

		var entry CostEntry
		entry.Timestamp = timestamp.Format("2006-01-02 15:04:05")
		entry.TimeApprox = timestamp.Format("15:04")
		entry.ContextTokensUsed = 0
		entry.RequestCost = 0.0
		entry.TotalCost = totalCost
		entry.HasImages = "No"
		entry.Phase = "User Input"
		entry.ContextPercentage = "0%"
		entry.CostNotes = "User feedback message"
		entry.SearchTermInTranscript = "user_feedback"

		// Handle different message types
		if msg.Type == "say" && msg.Say == "text" && msg.Text != "" && isFirstEntry {
			// First entry - main user request
			entry.RequestSummary = "Task Request: " + msg.Text
			entry.AskSay = `"say": "text"`
			entry.Text = msg.Text
			entry.ClineAction = "Task Description"
			entry.ToolUsed = "N/A"
			isFirstEntry = false
			apiCosts = append(apiCosts, entry)
			requestCounter++
		} else if msg.Type == "say" && msg.Say == "user_feedback" && msg.Text != "" {
			// User feedback entries
			entry.RequestSummary = "User Input: " + msg.Text
			entry.AskSay = `"say": "user_feedback"`
			entry.Text = msg.Text
			entry.ClineAction = "User Feedback"
			entry.ToolUsed = "N/A"
			apiCosts = append(apiCosts, entry)
			requestCounter++
		} else if msg.Type == "say" && msg.Say == "api_req_started" && msg.Text != "" {
			// API request entries
			var apiData APIRequestData
			if err := json.Unmarshal([]byte(msg.Text), &apiData); err == nil {
				totalCost += apiData.Cost
				entry.RequestSummary = "API Request: " + apiData.Request[:min(50, len(apiData.Request))] + "..."
				entry.AskSay = `"say": "api_req_started"`
				entry.Text = msg.Text
				entry.RequestCost = apiData.Cost
				entry.TotalCost = totalCost
				entry.ContextTokensUsed = apiData.TokensIn + apiData.TokensOut
				entry.ClineAction = "API request started"
				entry.ToolUsed = "API Request"
				entry.Phase = "Completion"
				entry.SearchTermInTranscript = "api_request"
				entry.CostNotes = "ACTUAL cost from Cline interface"
				apiCosts = append(apiCosts, entry)
				requestCounter++
			}
		} else if msg.Type == "ask" && msg.Text != "" {
			// Tool usage entries
			entry.RequestSummary = ""
			entry.AskSay = `"ask": "tool"`
			entry.Text = msg.Text
			entry.ClineAction = "Tool operation"
			entry.ToolUsed = "ask operation"
			entry.Phase = "Exploration"
			entry.SearchTermInTranscript = "ask"
			apiCosts = append(apiCosts, entry)
			requestCounter++
		}
	}

	if len(apiCosts) == 0 {
		fmt.Println("‚ö†Ô∏è  No API costs found in ui_messages.json")
		return
	}

	// Sort all entries by timestamp chronologically
	sort.Slice(apiCosts, func(i, j int) bool {
		timeI, errI := time.Parse("2006-01-02 15:04:05", apiCosts[i].Timestamp)
		timeJ, errJ := time.Parse("2006-01-02 15:04:05", apiCosts[j].Timestamp)
		if errI != nil || errJ != nil {
			return false
		}
		return timeI.Before(timeJ)
	})

	// Calculate context percentages
	maxTokens := 0
	for _, cost := range apiCosts {
		if cost.ContextTokensUsed > maxTokens {
			maxTokens = cost.ContextTokensUsed
		}
	}

	for i := range apiCosts {
		if maxTokens > 0 {
			percentage := int((float64(apiCosts[i].ContextTokensUsed) / float64(maxTokens)) * 100)
			apiCosts[i].ContextPercentage = fmt.Sprintf("%d%%", percentage)
		} else {
			apiCosts[i].ContextPercentage = "0%"
		}
	}

	// Write to CSV file
	file, err := os.Create(csvFile)
	if err != nil {
		log.Fatalf("‚ùå Error creating CSV file: %v", err)
	}
	defer file.Close()

	writer := csv.NewWriter(file)
	defer writer.Flush()

	// Write header with new structure: Request Summary, Ask/Say, Cost, Text, Timestamp, Context tokens used, Total cost, [existing columns]
	header := []string{
		"Request Summary", "Ask/Say", "Cost", "Text", "Timestamp", "Context tokens used", "Total cost",
		"User_Request", "Cline_Action", "Tool_Used", "Has_Images", "Phase", "Context_Percentage",
		"Search_Term_In_Transcript", "Cost_Notes", "Time_Approx",
	}
	if err := writer.Write(header); err != nil {
		log.Fatalf("‚ùå Error writing CSV header: %v", err)
	}

	// Write entries with new structure
	for _, entry := range apiCosts {
		record := []string{
			entry.RequestSummary,
			entry.AskSay,
			entry.Text,
			fmt.Sprintf("%.6f", entry.RequestCost),
			entry.Timestamp,
			strconv.Itoa(entry.ContextTokensUsed),
			fmt.Sprintf("%.6f", entry.TotalCost),
			entry.UserRequest,
			entry.ClineAction,
			entry.ToolUsed,
			entry.HasImages,
			entry.Phase,
			entry.ContextPercentage,
			entry.SearchTermInTranscript,
			entry.CostNotes,
			entry.TimeApprox,
		}
		if err := writer.Write(record); err != nil {
			log.Fatalf("‚ùå Error writing CSV record: %v", err)
		}
	}

	fmt.Printf("‚úÖ Successfully updated %s with %d cost entries\n", csvFile, len(apiCosts))
	fmt.Printf("üí∞ Total cost for this task: $%.6f\n", totalCost)
}

// Helper functions
func isCommonWord(word string) bool {
	commonWords := map[string]bool{
		"the": true, "and": true, "for": true, "are": true, "but": true, "not": true,
		"you": true, "all": true, "can": true, "had": true, "her": true, "was": true,
		"one": true, "our": true, "out": true, "day": true, "get": true, "has": true,
		"him": true, "his": true, "how": true, "man": true, "new": true, "now": true,
		"old": true, "see": true, "two": true, "way": true, "who": true, "boy": true,
		"did": true, "its": true, "let": true, "put": true, "say": true, "she": true,
		"too": true, "use": true, "want": true, "with": true, "this": true, "that": true,
	}
	return commonWords[strings.ToLower(word)]
}

func min(a, b int) int {
	if a < b {
		return a
	}
	return b
}
